<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec62-OrthogonalSets" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Orthogonal Sets</title>

  <p>
    Recall back in the last section (and the next section), we saw that two vectors are <alert>orthogonal</alert> if their <em>inner product</em> is <m>0</m>. 
    Similarly, we can define <term>orthogonal sets</term> as a set of orthogonal vectors. 
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-OrthogonalSet">
    <title>Orthogonal Sets</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A set of vectors <m>\set{\v{v}_1, \v{v}_2 , \ldots, \v{v}_p}</m> is an <term>orthogonal set</term> if each pair of distinct vectors from this set is orthogonal. 
            That is, 
            <md>
                \v{v}_i \cdot \v{v}_j = 0
            </md>
            whenever <m>i \neq j</m>. 
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <example>
    <p>
        Let <m>\v{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, <m>\v{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, and <m>\v{v}_3 = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{2} \\ -2 \\ \frac{7}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
        Is this set <m>\set{\v{v}_1, \v{v}_2, \v{v}_3}</m> an orthogonal set? 
    </p>

    <p>
        If this is an orthogonal set, then each pair of the distinct vectors is orthogonal. 
        We can form three pairs of distinct vectors in the set, and we will check their orthogonality respectively: 
        <md>
            <mrow> \v{v}_1 \cdot \v{v}_2 \amp= \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = -3 + 2 + 1 = 0</mrow>
            <mrow> \v{v}_2 \cdot \v{v}_3 \amp= \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{2} \\ -2 \\ \frac{7}{2} \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{2} - 4 + \frac{7}{2} = 0</mrow>
            <mrow> \v{v}_1 \cdot \v{v}_3 \amp= \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{2} \\ -2 \\ \frac{7}{2} \end{bmatrix} = -\frac{3}{2} - 2 + \frac{7}{2} = 0</mrow>
        </md>
        Observe that each pair of distinct vectors in the set is orthogonal. 
        Hence this is an orthogonal set. 
    </p>
  </example>

  <p>
    Sometimes we want to only focus on the direction of a vector. 
    Since the length of a vector has nothing to do with its direction, we want to minimize the effect of the length by <alert>making the length to be <m>1</m></alert>. 
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-UnitVector">
    <title>Unit Vectors</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A vector with length <m>1</m> is called a <term>unit vector</term>. 
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    Given a non-zero vector <m>\v{v}</m>, we can make its length to be <m>1</m> by <alert>dividing it by its length</alert>. 
    That is, a unit vector in the same direction as <m>\v{v}</m> is
    <md>
        \v{u} = \frac{\v{v}}{\|\v{v}\|}
    </md>
    This process of creating a normal vector <m>\v{u}</m> from <m>\v{v}</m> is called <term>normalizing <m>\v{v}</m></term>. 
  </p>

  <p>
    Given an orthogonal set, we can even normalize each vector in this set! 
    This set is called the <term>orthonormal set</term>. 
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-OrthonormalSet">
    <title>Orthonormal Sets</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A set <m>\set{\v{u}_1, \v{u}_2, \ldots, \v{u}_p}</m> is an <term>orthonormal set</term> if it is an orthogonal set of unit vectors. 
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <example>
    <p>
        We showed that, in the previous example, that <m>\set{\v{v}_1, \v{v}_2, \v{v}_3}</m> is an orthogonal set, where <m>\v{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, <m>\v{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, and <m>\v{v}_3 = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{2} \\ -2 \\ \frac{7}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
        Is this set also an orthonormal set? 
    </p>

    <p>
        The answer is no since none of the three vectors have the length of <m>1</m>. 
    </p>

    <p>
        <alert>But we can make an orthonormal set out of it</alert> by normalizing each vector. 
        Since normalization (aka rescaling the vector to have the length of <m>1</m>) will not change the direction, the orthogonality remains. 
    </p>

    <p>
        Observe that
        <md>
            <mrow> \|\v{v}_1\| \amp= \sqrt{3^2 + 1^2 + 1^2} = \sqrt{11} </mrow>
            <mrow> \|\v{v}_2\| \amp= \sqrt{(-1)^2 + 2^2 + 1^2} = \sqrt{6} </mrow>
            <mrow> \|\v{v}_3\| \amp= \sqrt{\lp -\frac{1}{2} \rp^2 + (-2)^2 + \lp \frac{7}{2} \rp^2} = \frac{\sqrt{66}}{2} </mrow>
        </md>
        Then we can normalize each vector by dividing it by its lengths: 
        <md>
            <mrow>\v{u}_1 \amp= \frac{\v{v}_1}{\|\v{v}_1\|} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{11}}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{3}{\sqrt{11}} \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{11}} \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{11}} \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            <mrow>\v{u}_2 \amp= \frac{\v{v}_2}{\|\v{v}_2\|} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \\ \frac{2}{\sqrt{6}} \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            <mrow>\v{u}_3 \amp= \frac{\v{v}_3}{\|\v{v}_3\|} = \frac{2}{\sqrt{66}}\begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{2} \\ -2 \\ \frac{7}{2} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{\sqrt{66}} \\ -\frac{4}{\sqrt{66}} \\ \frac{7}{\sqrt{66}} \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
        </md>
        The set <m>\set{\v{u}_1, \v{u}_2, \v{u}_3}</m> is now an orthonormal set!
    </p>
  </example>

  <p>
    But why do we want orthogonal/orthonormal sets? 
    That is because these sets are <em>linearly independent</em> so they can become some bases for some subspaces. 
    Also, things are working out nicely with orthogonal/orthonormal bases, so we like to work with them. 
  </p>

  <p>
    If we want an orthogonal basis for a subspace, we can produce it using the <term>Gram-Schmidt Process</term>. 
    We will not be covering it in this class.
    Feel free to look into it if you are interested.
    You should be able to understand the process just fine, as the trick to make the process work is through projection that we learned before!
  </p>
  
  <worksheet xml:id="ws-sec62">
    <title>Some Exercises for This Section</title>
    
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Richard included some practice problems that cover some main concepts in this section. 
        You don't need to turn it in, but you are highly encouraged to work on this with your classmates. 
        The problems here may end up being in-class practice problems, homework problems, and/or exam problems. 
        Reach out to Richard for help if you get stuck or have any questions. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Only the final answers are included to some of the problems for you to check your result. 
        If you want to check your work, talk to Richard and he is happy to discuss the process with you. 
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <exercisegroup>
        <introduction>
            <p>Determine which of the following sets of vectors are orthogonal.</p>
        </introduction>
        
        <exercise number="6.2.3">
            <statement>
                <me>\begin{bmatrix}2\\ -7\\ -1\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}-6\\ -3\\ 9\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}3\\ 1\\ -1\end{bmatrix}</me>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="6.2.5">
            <statement>
                <me>\begin{bmatrix}3\\ -2\\ 1\\ 3\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}-1\\ 3\\ -3\\ 4\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}3\\ 8\\ 7\\ 0\end{bmatrix}</me>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup>
        <introduction>
            <p>In Exercise 9, .</p>
        </introduction>

        <exercise number="6.2.9">
            <statement>
              <p>
                show that <m>\{u_{1},u_{2},u_{3}\}</m> is an orthogonal basis for <m>\mathbb{R}^{3}</m>. Then express <m>x</m> as a linear combination of the <m>u</m>'s. 
                <me>u_{1}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\ 0\\ 1\end{bmatrix}, \quad u_{2}=\begin{bmatrix}-1\\ 4\\ 1\end{bmatrix}, \quad u_{3}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\ 1\\ -2\end{bmatrix}, \quad \text{and} \quad x=\begin{bmatrix}8\\ -4\\ -3\end{bmatrix}</me>
              </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercise number="6.2.11">
        <statement>
            <p>Compute the orthogonal projection of <m>\begin{bmatrix}1\\ 7\end{bmatrix}</m> onto the line through <m>\begin{bmatrix}-4\\ 2\end{bmatrix}</m> and the origin.</p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="6.2.13">
        <statement>
            <p>Let <m>y=\begin{bmatrix}2\\ 3\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>u=\begin{bmatrix}-3\\ 4\end{bmatrix}</m>. Write <m>y</m> as the sum of two orthogonal vectors, one in Span <m>\{u\}</m> and one orthogonal to <m>u</m>.</p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercisegroup>
        <introduction>
            <p>In Exercises 17 and 21, determine which sets of vectors are orthonormal. If a set is only orthogonal, normalize the vectors to produce an orthonormal set.</p>
        </introduction>

        <exercise number="6.2.17">
            <statement>
                <me>\begin{bmatrix}1/3\\ 1/3\\ 1/3\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}-1/2\\ 0\\ 1/2\end{bmatrix}</me>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="6.2.21">
            <statement>
                <me>\begin{bmatrix}1/\sqrt{10}\\ 3/\sqrt{20}\\ 3/\sqrt{20}\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}3/\sqrt{10}\\ -1/\sqrt{20}\\ -1/\sqrt{20}\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}0\\ -1/\sqrt{2}\\ 1/\sqrt{2}\end{bmatrix}</me>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup>
        <introduction>
            <p>In Exercises 23-29, all vectors are in <m>\mathbb{R}^{n}</m>. Mark each statement True or False (T/F). Justify each answer.</p>
        </introduction>

        <exercise number="6.2.23">
            <statement>
                <p>(T/F) Not every linearly independent set in <m>\mathbb{R}^{n}</m> is an orthogonal set.</p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="6.2.25">
            <statement>
                <p>(T/F) If <m>y</m> is a linear combination of nonzero vectors from an orthogonal set, then the weights in the linear combination can be computed without row operations on a matrix.</p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="6.2.27">
            <statement>
                <p>(T/F) If the vectors in an orthogonal set of nonzero vectors are normalized, then some of the new vectors may not be orthogonal.</p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="6.2.29">
            <statement>
                <p>(T/F) A matrix with orthonormal columns is an orthogonal matrix.</p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </worksheet>

</section>